result.execSummary:
The defendant Jessica M James was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Jessica M James in court with attorney Victoria Mccandless.  Molly M Schmidt appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
cab
Parties are in court for sentencing.
Statements by each counsel  as to sentencing.  
As to counts 1 and 2:
Court sentenced the defendant to serve 9 months in the House of Correction as to count 1 and 3 months in the House of Correction as to count 2, consecutive, with credit for 3 days served.  
Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for 24 months, concurrent,  with the following conditions:
- Serve 60 days in the House of Correction; STAYED pending review.
- Complete a course in anger management.
- Attend parenting classes.
- AODA assessment; comply with any treatment.
- Maintain absolute sobriety; random urine screens.
- Attend treatment and/or counseling as determined by the agent.
- No contact with the child unless approved by the court.  
- No contact with firearms.
- Pay DV surcharge plus all other costs and surcharges; civil judgment if not paid.
- Pay supervision fees.
- Obtain a DNA test and pay any surcharge.
